The paper deals with the problem of approximating constraint satisfaction problems, which is a central topic in computational complexity theory (cs.CC). The use of high-dimensional expanders is a key feature of the paper, which suggests that it could also be relevant to the subfield of theoretical computer science concerned with the study of expanders and their applications (cs.DS). The paper also makes use of spectral techniques, which are commonly used in information theory (cs.IT) and machine learning (cs.LG). Finally, the paper deals with hypergraphs, which are a natural generalization of graphs, and could therefore be relevant to the subfield of computational geometry (cs.CG).
